31	UNSOLVED_PYQ	Basic Electrical and Electronics Engineering - Dec 2023	2023	You are an elite expert AI parser specializing in Engineering Academic exams for RGPV University.\n\nCONTEXT:\nBuilding material for Branch: {branch_name}\nSubject: {subject_code} - {subject_name}\nDocument Type target: {document_type}\n\nYour task is to extract exact information from raw exam papers, syllabi, or notes (provided as text or images) and generate pristine, highly-accurate structured data for them.\nYou MUST output valid JSON conforming strictly to the requested schema.\nCRITICAL INSTRUCTION: DO NOT process or transcribe any Hindi text whatsoever. Extract and process ONLY the English versions of the questions.\nIMAGE INSTRUCTION: If a question or section does NOT contain an image or diagram in the source, set 'image_strategy' to null and 'image_details' to null. DO NOT invent or assume images exist.\nFor 'latex_answer' or any mathematical fields, use Markdown for normal text and wrap ANY math in KaTeX delimiters ($ for inline, $$ for block formulas).	raw_docs/bt-104-basic-electrical-and-electronics-engineering-dec-2023.pdf	\N	COMPLETED	1	1	1	1	{"questions": [{"part": "a", "unit": null, "marks": 7, "has_or_choice": false, "image_details": null, "question_text": "Use mesh analysis to determine the three mesh current in the circuit of the figure below.", "image_strategy": null}, {"part": "b", "unit": null, "marks": 7, "has_or_choice": false, "image_details": "Circuit diagram with resistors and voltage/current sources. Left branch: 5 Ohm resistor. Top branch: 4 Ohm resistor, then V0, then 1 Ohm resistor. Middle vertical branch: 3 Ohm resistor, then a 9V voltage source (positive up), then ground. The 4 Ohm, 1 Ohm, and 3 Ohm resistors form a mesh with a 3V voltage source on the right. Current direction implied by voltage source polarity.", "question_text": "Using super position, find the $V_0$ in the circuit shown in figure below.", "image_strategy": "CANVAS", "recreated_image_url": "https://s3.us-east-005.backblazeb2.com/campusprep/recreated/9a198ae5-94a8-49b9-a34b-d5cfe468dfc2.png?X-Amz-Algorithm=AWS4-HMAC-SHA256&X-Amz-Credential=005ff988bd983190000000001%2F20260226%2Fus-east-005%2Fs3%2Faws4_request&X-Amz-Date=20260226T032015Z&X-Amz-Expires=3600&X-Amz-SignedHeaders=host&X-Amz-Signature=16821cad166b7f49b1284c5080d901b7bc006bd90ab26ac3baaced010fc2db04", "recreated_html_source": "<canvas id=\\"canvas\\" style=\\"width:100%;max-width:800px;height:auto;\\"></canvas>\\n<script>\\nconst canvas = document.getElementById('canvas');\\nconst ctx = canvas.getContext('2d');\\n\\n// logical size\\nconst W = 600;\\nconst H = 400;\\ncanvas.width = W;\\ncanvas.height = H;\\n\\n// styling\\nconst wireColor = '#475569';      // slate-700\\nconst resistorColor = '#4F46E5';  // indigo-600\\nconst sourceColor = '#10B981';    // emerald-500\\nctx.lineCap = 'round';\\nctx.font = '14px sans-serif';\\nctx.textAlign = 'center';\\nctx.textBaseline = 'middle';\\n\\n// helper to draw a straight wire\\nfunction drawWire(x1, y1, x2, y2) {\\n  ctx.strokeStyle = wireColor;\\n  ctx.lineWidth = 2;\\n  ctx.beginPath();\\n  ctx.moveTo(x1, y1);\\n  ctx.lineTo(x2, y2);\\n  ctx.stroke();\\n}\\n\\n// draw a resistor as a rectangle with label\\nfunction drawResistor(x1, y1, x2, y2, label) {\\n  const length = Math.hypot(x2 - x1, y2 - y1);\\n  const angle = Math.atan2(y2 - y1, x2 - x1);\\n  const cx = (x1 + x2) / 2;\\n  const cy = (y1 + y2) / 2;\\n  const rectW = 30;\\n  const rectH = 12;\\n\\n  ctx.save();\\n  ctx.translate(cx, cy);\\n  ctx.rotate(angle);\\n  ctx.fillStyle = resistorColor;\\n  ctx.fillRect(-rectW/2, -rectH/2, rectW, rectH);\\n  ctx.strokeStyle = '#fff';\\n  ctx.lineWidth = 1.5;\\n  ctx.strokeRect(-rectW/2, -rectH/2, rectW, rectH);\\n  ctx.fillStyle = '#fff';\\n  ctx.fillText(label, 0, 0);\\n  ctx.restore();\\n\\n  // wires to the resistor ends\\n  const offset = rectW/2;\\n  const xA = cx - Math.cos(angle)*offset;\\n  const yA = cy - Math.sin(angle)*offset;\\n  const xB = cx + Math.cos(angle)*offset;\\n  const yB = cy + Math.sin(angle)*offset;\\n  drawWire(x1, y1, xA, yA);\\n  drawWire(xB, yB, x2, y2);\\n}\\n\\n// draw a voltage source (circle with + and -)\\nfunction drawVoltageSource(x1, y1, x2, y2, label, polarity = '+') {\\n  const length = Math.hypot(x2 - x1, y2 - y1);\\n  const angle = Math.atan2(y2 - y1, x1 - x2); // direction from positive to negative\\n  const cx = (x1 + x2) / 2;\\n  const cy = (y1 + y2) / 2;\\n  const radius = 14;\\n\\n  ctx.save();\\n  ctx.translate(cx, cy);\\n  ctx.rotate(Math.atan2(y2 - y1, x2 - x1));\\n  // circle\\n  ctx.strokeStyle = sourceColor;\\n  ctx.lineWidth = 2;\\n  ctx.beginPath();\\n  ctx.arc(0, 0, radius, 0, Math.PI * 2);\\n  ctx.stroke();\\n  // terminals\\n  ctx.beginPath();\\n  ctx.moveTo(-radius, 0);\\n  ctx.lineTo(-radius - 10, 0);\\n  ctx.moveTo(radius, 0);\\n  ctx.lineTo(radius + 10, 0);\\n  ctx.stroke();\\n  // polarity\\n  ctx.fillStyle = sourceColor;\\n  ctx.font = '12px sans-serif';\\n  ctx.textAlign = 'center';\\n  ctx.textBaseline = 'bottom';\\n  ctx.fillText(polarity, -radius/2, -radius-2);\\n  ctx.textBaseline = 'top';\\n  ctx.fillText(polarity === '+' ? '-' : '+', radius/2, radius+2);\\n  // label\\n  ctx.fillStyle = '#000';\\n  ctx.font = '14px sans-serif';\\n  ctx.textBaseline = 'middle';\\n  ctx.fillText(label, 0, 0);\\n  ctx.restore();\\n\\n  // wires to the terminals\\n  const termLen = radius + 10;\\n  const xA = cx - Math.cos(angle) * termLen;\\n  const yA = cy - Math.sin(angle) * termLen;\\n  const xB = cx + Math.cos(angle) * termLen;\\n  const yB = cy + Math.sin(angle) * termLen;\\n  drawWire(x1, y1, xA, yA);\\n  drawWire(xB, yB, x2, y2);\\n}\\n\\n// draw ground symbol\\nfunction drawGround(x, y) {\\n  const gap = 6;\\n  ctx.strokeStyle = wireColor;\\n  ctx.lineWidth = 2;\\n  ctx.beginPath();\\n  ctx.moveTo(x, y);\\n  ctx.lineTo(x, y + gap);\\n  ctx.stroke();\\n\\n  const widths = [20, 14, 8];\\n  for (let i = 0; i < widths.length; i++) {\\n    const w = widths[i];\\n    const yy = y + gap + i * 4;\\n    ctx.beginPath();\\n    ctx.moveTo(x - w/2, yy);\\n    ctx.lineTo(x + w/2, yy);\\n    ctx.stroke();\\n  }\\n}\\n\\n// Coordinates\\nconst leftX = 120, rightX = 480;\\nconst topY = 80, bottomY = 300;\\n\\n// Nodes\\nconst TL = {x:leftX, y:topY};\\nconst TR = {x:rightX, y:topY};\\nconst BL = {x:leftX, y:bottomY};\\nconst BR = {x:rightX, y:bottomY};\\n\\n// ---- Left vertical branch (5Ω) ----\\ndrawResistor(TL.x, TL.y, BL.x, BL.y, '5Ω');\\n\\n// ---- Top horizontal branch (4Ω – V0 – 1Ω) ----\\nlet curX = TL.x;\\nconst segLen = 80;\\n\\n// 4Ω resistor\\ndrawResistor(curX, TL.y, curX+segLen, TL.y, '4Ω');\\ncurX += segLen;\\n\\n// V0 source (positive on left side)\\ndrawVoltageSource(curX, TL.y, curX+segLen, TL.y, 'V₀', '+');\\ncurX += segLen;\\n\\n// 1Ω resistor\\ndrawResistor(curX, TL.y, curX+segLen, TL.y, '1Ω');\\ncurX += segLen;\\n\\n// wire to TR\\ndrawWire(curX, TL.y, TR.x, TR.y);\\n\\n// ---- Right vertical branch (3V source) ----\\nlet curY = TR.y;\\nconst vSeg = 80;\\ndrawVoltageSource(TR.x, curY, TR.x, curY+vSeg, '3V', '+');\\ncurY += vSeg;\\ndrawWire(TR.x, curY, BR.x, BR.y);\\n\\n// ---- Bottom horizontal branch (3Ω – 9V – ground) ----\\ncurX = BL.x;\\nconst botSeg = 80;\\n\\n// 3Ω resistor\\ndrawResistor(curX, BL.y, curX+botSeg, BL.y, '3Ω');\\ncurX += botSeg;\\n\\n// 9V source (positive up)\\ndrawVoltageSource(curX, BL.y, curX+botSeg, BL.y, '9V', '+');\\ncurX += botSeg;\\n\\n// wire to ground position\\ndrawWire(curX, BL.y, BR.x - 30, BR.y);\\n\\n// ground symbol\\ndrawGround(BR.x, BR.y);\\n</script>"}, {"part": "a", "unit": null, "marks": 7, "has_or_choice": false, "image_details": null, "question_text": "Discuss about the Star Delta transformation using suitable example.", "image_strategy": null}, {"part": "b", "unit": null, "marks": 7, "has_or_choice": false, "image_details": null, "question_text": "Explain the following terms pertaining to an A.C. wave\\ni) Time period\\nii) RMS value\\niii) Average value\\niv) Form factor", "image_strategy": null}, {"part": "a", "unit": null, "marks": 7, "has_or_choice": false, "image_details": null, "question_text": "A choke coil has resistance of $10$ ohm and inductance of $0.05\\\\, H$ is connected with $100\\\\, \\\\mu F$ capacitor in series across $200\\\\, V, 50\\\\, Hz$ supply.\\n\\nCalculate the following\\ni) Impedance\\nii) Current\\niii) Power factor\\niv) Real power", "image_strategy": null}, {"part": "b", "unit": null, "marks": 7, "has_or_choice": false, "image_details": null, "question_text": "Derive an expression of impedance, current, power factor, power in watts in RLC series circuit.", "image_strategy": null}, {"part": "a", "unit": null, "marks": 7, "has_or_choice": false, "image_details": null, "question_text": "Discuss about active, reactive and apparent power in series RLC circuits.", "image_strategy": null}, {"part": "b", "unit": null, "marks": 7, "has_or_choice": false, "image_details": null, "question_text": "Discuss about magnetization characteristics of ferromagnetic material.", "image_strategy": null}, {"part": "a", "unit": null, "marks": 7, "has_or_choice": false, "image_details": null, "question_text": "Discuss the laws of Electromagnetic induction.", "image_strategy": null}, {"part": "b", "unit": null, "marks": 7, "has_or_choice": false, "image_details": null, "question_text": "Open circuit and short circuit test on a single phase transformer gave the following results.\\n$V_0 = 200\\\\, V, I_0 = 0.7\\\\, A, W_0 = 20\\\\, Watt$ Test from primary side\\n$V_c = 10\\\\, V, I_c = 10\\\\, A, W_c = 40\\\\, Watt$ test from secondary side.\\nDetermine the equivalent circuit parameters referred to primary side.", "image_strategy": null}, {"part": "a", "unit": null, "marks": 7, "has_or_choice": false, "image_details": null, "question_text": "Draw and explain the complete Torque-slip characteristics of 3 phase induction motor.", "image_strategy": null}, {"part": "b", "unit": null, "marks": 7, "has_or_choice": false, "imag